Hi,

On Sun, 18 Jun 2000, Pasi Lagerroos wrote:
> You started with the game shogo but still you relesed heretic2 before
> that... why? 

That's a simple answer: Shogo is *HUGE*. It has nearly half a million
lines of code (400.000, to be precise). It's completely C++, which was at
first a problem due to compiler difficulties. The engine is more or less a
complete abstraction layer to the operating system, not just a simple 3d
engine. It features stuff like memory handling (ok, easy to do), threads
(very difficult, because they are handled more like Java than Amiga),
interprocess communication, and all that stuff normally found inside an
operating system core.

Of course, there's also the 3d engine itself, which is completely D3D.

OTOH, Heretic 2 is, as a typical iD engine design, very portable. It uses
OpenGL for rendering, and uses a very good encapsulation at the bottom. So
at first, Heretic 2 made tremendous progress. When it became clear that it
would soon be beta, most of us concentrated on Heretic 2. We all have
bills to pay, so getting something to the market is an important
consideration. 

So there where only two people left working on it. And we had lots of bad
luck in that time. We experienced lots of hardware breakdown, and
replacement is very hard to get, and extremely expensive (We had to get
three additional PPC boards). 

> Can somebody give me some estimates when will these games
> be relesed or is there any chance to get a demo of shogo or sin?

Shogo may be ready in a month or so. It's hard to estimate, because we are
still working on the hardware renderer (the software renderer is already
finished). There are some problems with the conversion D3D->OpenGL.

Sin is going on rather well, but it's hard to say when it's in a state
that can be put out as a demo. 

We hope for a Q3 2000 release of both games.

